<h2>What Is Trauma?</h2>
<p>Trauma is the lasting psychological impact of events or experiences that overwhelm a person's capacity to cope. It is not defined by the event itself but by its effect on the nervous system and sense of self and safety. What traumatises one person may not traumatise another — this reflects differences in prior history, support systems, and neurobiological factors, not strength or weakness.</p>

<p>Trauma falls into two broad categories. Single-incident trauma (Type I) involves a discrete traumatic event — an accident, assault, natural disaster, medical emergency. Complex trauma (Type II or C-PTSD) involves repeated, prolonged, or developmental trauma — childhood abuse or neglect, domestic violence, chronic medical trauma, prolonged combat exposure. These respond to overlapping but somewhat different treatment approaches.</p>

<h2>How Trauma Gets Stuck</h2>
<p>Traumatic memories are processed differently from ordinary memories. Instead of being integrated into autobiographical memory as something that happened in the past, they remain fragmented, emotionally charged, and present-tense — as if the threat is still ongoing. This is why trauma survivors re-experience events through intrusive memories, nightmares, and flashbacks rather than simply recalling them.</p>

<p>The nervous system also adapts to chronic threat through patterns of hyperarousal (hypervigilance, startle response, sleep disruption, irritability) and hypoarousal (emotional numbing, disconnection, dissociation). These responses made sense during the trauma; they become problematic when they persist long after the threat has passed.</p>

<h2>Evidence-Based Trauma Treatments</h2>

<h3>EMDR (Eye Movement Desensitisation and Reprocessing)</h3>
<p>EMDR uses bilateral stimulation (typically eye movements, but also tapping or sounds) while the client brings traumatic memories to mind. The mechanism is debated, but the outcome data is robust — EMDR produces significant reduction in PTSD symptoms and has WHO endorsement as a first-line trauma treatment. It is particularly effective for single-incident trauma and often produces results faster than talk-based approaches.</p>

<h3>CPT (Cognitive Processing Therapy)</h3>
<p>CPT targets the "stuck points" — the beliefs trauma generates about oneself, others, and the world ("It was my fault," "The world is completely dangerous," "I can't trust anyone"). Through structured written assignments and cognitive work, CPT helps people develop more accurate, adaptive beliefs. It has strong evidence for PTSD from multiple trauma types.</p>

<h3>PE (Prolonged Exposure)</h3>
<p>PE involves systematic, graduated exposure to trauma memories and avoided situations. By staying with distressing material long enough for habituation to occur — rather than escaping it — the fear response reduces. PE has decades of evidence behind it for PTSD.</p>

<h3>Trauma-Focused CBT (TF-CBT)</h3>
<p>TF-CBT combines trauma-processing work with cognitive and behavioural techniques. It is particularly well-evidenced for childhood trauma and can be adapted for adults.</p>

<h2>Online Delivery of Trauma Therapy</h2>
<p>EMDR, CPT, and TF-CBT have all been studied in online formats with comparable outcomes to in-person delivery. Online trauma therapy offers access to specialists who may not be geographically available — important given that trauma-trained therapists are not evenly distributed.</p>

<p>For complex trauma, phased treatment is typically recommended: stabilisation and skill-building before trauma processing. A therapist will assess your window of tolerance and readiness before beginning exposure-based work.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<p><strong>Do I have to relive the trauma to recover?</strong><br/>
Effective trauma therapy involves engaging with traumatic memories — but in a controlled, titrated way, at a pace that keeps you within your window of tolerance. It does not mean flooding yourself with the worst aspects of the trauma. A skilled therapist manages this carefully.</p>

<p><strong>What if I can't remember much of the trauma?</strong><br/>
Fragmented or incomplete memory is common with trauma, particularly early childhood trauma or dissociative responses. Therapy doesn't require complete memory recall to be effective. EMDR in particular can work with partial, sensory, or emotional memory fragments.</p>

<p><strong>Is it safe to do trauma therapy online?</strong><br/>
Yes, with a trained therapist. Online trauma therapy has been used successfully for decades, including with military veterans and disaster survivors. The key is working with a therapist experienced in trauma, not a generalist.</p>

